-- Sub-Saharan African Equity Movers: Continental Re, Co-Operative Bank Gain
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-06-17T17:17:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-17/sub-saharan-african-equity-movers-continental-re-co-operative-bank-gain.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose 0.3
percent to 1,633.95, a third day of gains, at the close in Port
Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  fell for a third day, losing 0.3
percent to 73.66 in Nairobi.  
 The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  advanced 0.8
percent to 25,913.44, according to Bloomberg data, its fourth
day of gains.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  climbed 12.25, or 1.6
percent, to 773.27 in Windhoek, while the  Ghana Stock Exchange
All-Share Index  added 0.7 percent to 6,481.76, its first advance
in 10 days.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Continental Reinsurance Plc  (CONTINSU NL), a Nigerian
insurer, gained 5 kobo, or 4.6 percent, to 1.15 naira after it
said profit climbed 91 percent last year.  
 Co-operative Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (COOP KN), the country’s
fourth-biggest lender by assets, rose to the highest since the
bank first sold shares in December 2008 as analysts said the
bank may be benefiting from expanding in the region.  
 The stock rose 5.6 percent to 14.15 shillings. The shares
have risen 10 percent in the past six days. It first sold shares
in December 2008 at 9.5 shillings.  
 Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd.  (KNCB KN), the East African
nation’s biggest lender by branches, fell the most this month
before a rights offer that will give investors the chance to buy
cheaper shares,  Aly Khan Satchu , a Nairobi-based independent
analyst, said in a phone interview today.  
 The stock retreated 50 cents, or 2.4 percent, to 20.25
shillings.  
